President Barack Obama has issued a proclamation declaring May 6, 2010, as a National Day of Prayer in the United States. The proclamation recognizes the historical importance of prayer in American society and encourages citizens to give thanks and pray for the nation. President Obama calls for prayers for those affected by natural disasters, such as Haiti and Chile, as well as for the families of the West Virginia miners and the people of Poland who lost their leaders. He also requests prayers for the safety of the armed forces and their families, as well as for the well-being of communities and the aspiration for a just and peaceful world. The President emphasizes that individuals should pray or give thanks according to their own faiths and consciences.